  "prompt": "How does the fuel reserve in a car work?",
  "response": "The fuel reserve in a car typically refers to the amount of fuel left when the fuel gauge indicates that the tank is near empty. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Fuel Gauge:** The fuel gauge in a car is connected to the fuel tank via a sensor, usually a float-type sensor that helps to monitor the fuel level. When the fuel level drops to a certain point, the gauge indicates that the fuel is low.\n\n2. **Reserve Indicator:** When the fuel level gets critically low, an indicator light (often a yellow or orange fuel pump icon) will illuminate on the dashboard. This is commonly referred to as the \"low fuel warning light,\" and it alerts the driver that the vehicle has entered its reserve fuel level.\n\n3. **Reserve Fuel Capacity:** Most cars have a reserve fuel capacity that typically ranges from 1 to 3 gallons. This reserve is an intentional design feature meant to give drivers some extra mileage to find a fuel station. The exact amount can vary depending on the vehicle make and model.\n\n4. **Mileage on Reserve:** The distance you can travel on the reserve fuel depends on factors like the specific reserve capacity of your car, the fuel efficiency of the vehicle, driving conditions, and your driving habits. In many vehicles, this range can be roughly 30 to 50 miles, but it's always ideal to refuel as soon as possible once the low fuel indicator activates.\n\nUnderstanding how the fuel reserve works can help you avoid running out of fuel unexpectedly. Regularly checking the fuel gauge and refueling before it gets too low is recommended to maintain safe driving conditions.",
